            <td>$40</td>
            <td>20000mAh (74Wh)</td>
            <td>30W</td>
            <td>30W</td>
            <td>356g</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>Anker 737 PowerCore</strong> is the smaller sibling in Anker's lineup. It is $10 cheaper, 90 g lighter, and matches the 100W single-port PD — but it has only 12000mAh capacity (43 Wh), so it cannot fully charge a MacBook Pro. If you want a lighter power bank for short trips and can accept partial laptop charges, the 737 is a strong alternative. See our <a href="/reviews/anker-powercore-10000-review/">Anker PowerCore 10000 review</a> for the ultra-portable breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Ugreen Power Bank 20000 145W</strong> is the direct competitor at $89. It has the same capacity and 100W single-port PD, but lower total output (145W vs 200W) and a less polished smart display. It is $20 cheaper and nearly as good for most users — choose it if you want to save $20 and do not need 200W multi-port output.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Shargeek S3 Pro</strong> is the design-forward alternative at $129. It has a transparent chassis that shows the internal battery cells, and a color smart display — but it is $20 more, has lower total output (130W vs 200W), and the transparent design is a matter of taste. It is the most striking power bank on the market, but the Prime 20000 PD is the better all-rounder.</p>

      <p>The basic <strong>Anker PowerCore 20000</strong> at $40 is the budget pick. It has the same 20000mAh capacity but only 30W output — fine for charging a phone, but it trickle-charges a MacBook Pro at best and can discharge under load on some Mac models. For phone-only charging, the basic PowerCore is the value champion. For laptop charging, the Prime 20000 PD is one of the few options that actually works.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the Prime 20000 PD at full price if you charge a laptop on the go. The 100W single-port PD and 200W total output are unmatched at $109, and the smart display is genuinely useful in daily use. For laptop users who travel or work remotely, this is one of the few portable power banks that actually delivers laptop-grade charging.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. Anker runs frequent promotions on the Prime line during Prime Day, Black Friday, and back-to-school events, and we have seen it drop to $79 to $89 during those windows. A $20 to $30 discount is common and worth waiting a few weeks for if you are not in a rush.</p>

      <p>Skip the Prime 20000 PD and buy the basic Anker PowerCore 20000 if you only charge a phone. The basic PowerCore is $40, has the same capacity, and charges a phone at 30W — fine for most casual users. The Prime line is overkill for phone-only charging.</p>

      <p>Buy the Anker 737 PowerCore instead if you want a lighter power bank for shorter trips. The 737 is 90 g lighter, matches the 100W single-port PD, and is $10 cheaper — but it has only 12000mAh capacity, so it cannot fully charge a MacBook Pro. For day trips where you only need a partial laptop charge, the 737 is the better pick.</p>

      <p>Consider the Ugreen Power Bank 20000 145W if you want to save $20. It has the same capacity and 100W single-port PD, with lower total output (145W vs 200W) and a less polished display. For most users who charge one laptop at a time, the Ugreen is nearly as good for less money. Pair the Prime 20000 PD with a <a href="/reviews/best-external-ssd-backup/">portable SSD</a> and a <a href="/reviews/best-usb-c-hub-macbook/">USB-C hub</a> for a complete travel workstation.</p>

